    <p class="text-gray-300"><strong>Pantry and BCTV.</strong> In comparing Pantry and BCTV, we consider the straight line and RAM benchmarks of Figure 8. Because Pantry turns arithmetic operations into at most tens of constraints (&sect;2.2), we expect excellent performance on straight line computations; conversely, we expect these computations to be inefficient under BCTV because every operation pays  <span class="math">c_{\\rm cpu}</span>  (&sect;3.1, Fig. 5) to represent the logic of a CPU cycle (&sect;2.3, Fig. 2). For computations involving random memory access, however, BCTV should outperform Pantry because of the latter's expensive hashing (&sect;2.2).</p>

